      SPAC rules
   =20
 =20
People have two main objections to special purpose acquisition companies, t=
he blank-check companies that raise a pool of money from public investors a=
nd then use it to take some private company public. First: Sometimes it can=
 look like the=C2=A0private company=C2=A0is running a scam. Going public by=
 merging with a SPAC is an alternative to a traditional initial public offe=
ring with somewhat more relaxed rules. In particular, it is generally accep=
ted that SPAC targets can include=C2=A0projected future earnings=C2=A0in th=
eir filings marketing their deal, while IPO companies can=E2=80=99t. If you=
 are a high-tech company with big dreams but no revenue yet, it is nice to =
be able to say =E2=80=9Cwell look how good our 2025 revenue is.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0Then if your 2025 revenue also turns out to be zero, well, you know, tha=
t=E2=80=99s fine, mistakes happen. There is a =E2=80=9Csafe harbor for forw=
ard-looking statements=E2=80=9D; if your predictions were in good faith but=
 turn out to be wrong, you can=E2=80=99t get sued. IPO companies don=E2=80=
=99t get this safe harbor, but SPAC companies do.Second: Sometimes it can l=
ook like the SPAC sponsor is running a scam. The sponsor is the person who =
raises the pool of money and goes out and finds a private company to merge =
with. Generally she will put up a little bit of her own money to pay for la=
wyers etc., and if she completes a deal her reward will be shares in the pu=
blic company equal to 25% of the money raised.[1] This rubs people the wron=
g way, first of all, because 25% is just a really big commission.=C2=A0But =
also it creates bad incentives. SPACs have a limited life; generally they h=
ave to do a merger within two years. If the SPAC does a merger, the sponsor=
 gets 25% of the money raised. If the SPAC does not do a merger in time, it=
 has to give investors back their money, and the sponsor gets nothing. The =
sponsor is going to really, really, really want to do a deal. If she does a=
 deal that is=C2=A0bad, that is fine, for her. If the sponsor of a $100 mil=
lion SPAC gets a deal done, and the stock drops 20% after it closes,=C2=A0t=
hen she gets $20 million; if she doesn=E2=80=99t get the deal done she gets=
 zero. It=E2=80=99s the opposite for the shareholders of the SPAC: If the d=
eal doesn=E2=80=99t happen, they get their $100 million back; if it does, a=
nd drops 20%, then they only get $80 million and have a $20 million loss. T=
he shareholders have to approve the deal, but this gives the sponsor powerf=
ul incentives to be optimistic about the deal.The U.S. Securities and Excha=
nge Commission does not particularly like SPACs, and yesterday it proposed =
new rules to make clear its displeasure. There are a bunch of rules but bro=
adly speaking they are aimed at the two main problems I identified above.[2=
]=C2=A0First, the SEC wants to get rid of projections in SPACs, and general=
ly tighten up the rules around liability for how SPACs market themselves. T=
here is a sense now that if you do an IPO, everything you say in the IPO pr=
ospectus has to be true, while if you go public via SPAC you get a bit more=
 creative license. The SEC wants to do away with that and put SPACs and IPO=
s on equal footing.It does this in several ways. The main one is that it ge=
ts rid of the safe harbor for SPACs=E2=80=99 forward-looking statements. Th=
e safe harbor says that big existing public companies can make statements a=
bout the future, and as long as (1) they publish boilerplate warnings sayin=
g =E2=80=9Cthese statements might not come true=E2=80=9D and (2) they don=
=E2=80=99t have =E2=80=9Cactual knowledge ... that the statement was false =
or misleading,=E2=80=9D then they can=E2=80=99t be sued for them. But this =
is not true of companies doing an initial public offering; basically if the=
y say stuff that is wrong they can be sued. So in practice IPO documents do=
 not contain projections. Right now people seem to think (though it is  not=
 free from doubt) that SPACs are treated like regular public companies, but=
 the SEC=E2=80=99s new rule would treat them like IPO companies.[3]But ther=
e are also other rule changes that have the effect of warning everyone in t=
he vicinity of a SPAC that if the disclosure is wrong, they will get sued. =
The SEC will treat the de-SPAC merger =E2=80=94=C2=A0the transaction in whi=
ch the SPAC merges with the private company, taking it public =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0as a public offering of securities. It will treat the private company as=
 a =E2=80=9Cco-registrant=E2=80=9D of the SPAC, making it liable for everyt=
hing in the prospectus. An investment bank that underwrites the initial SPA=
C offering and also works on the de-SPAC merger will be treated as an under=
writer of that de-SPAC merger, potentially=C2=A0making=C2=A0it liable for=
=C2=A0errors in the merger prospectus. (Presumably this will increase the f=
ees that the banks charge SPACs.)On one level it is hard to object to this.=
 It is weird to have two ways of going public, one of which (a SPAC) allows=
 you to exaggerate and one of which (an IPO) does not. And when you put it =
like that it does seem like the not-exaggerating=C2=A0approach is preferabl=
e to the exaggerating=C2=A0one. Also there is  some evidence that (1) inves=
tors pay=C2=A0attention to optimistic projections in de-SPAC mergers and (2=
) those projections are  not very good, which you might expect from, you kn=
ow, being allowed to exaggerate.=C2=A0On the other hand. The intuitive sort=
ing between SPACs and IPOs, under the current rules, is not exactly =E2=80=
=9Creal companies do IPOs and fake companies do SPACs.=E2=80=9D It is more =
like =E2=80=9Ccompanies with a few years of impressive revenue growth do IP=
Os, while companies whose main product is still a prototype do SPACs.=E2=80=
=9D (This is not always true either way, by any means, but it is a rough he=
uristic.) If you are working on building a flying electric taxi or whatever=
, (1) that=E2=80=99s kind of cool, (2) it will cost a lot of money, (3) if =
it works you=E2=80=99ll probably make a lot of money and (4) it might not w=
ork. If you go to public-market investors and say =E2=80=9Chi, I want to bu=
ild flying electric taxis, my revenue last year was zero and I spend $50 mi=
llion on salaries and components,=E2=80=9D that is not a compelling pitch. =
If you go to them and say =E2=80=9Chi, I want to build flying electric taxi=
s, if all goes well we=E2=80=99ll bring in a billion dollars of revenue in =
2024,=E2=80=9D they will be like =E2=80=9Coh cool flying taxis!=E2=80=9DThi=
s is bad for them if you fail to build flying electric taxis and good for t=
hem if you succeed wildly. And of course you might be running a scam. But a=
gainst a general backdrop in which companies that go public are increasingl=
y old, large and established, there is something nice about SPACs being a w=
ay for companies to go public earlier. SPACs can be a way for public market=
s to provide venture-type capital to young ambitious companies, particularl=
y green-tech companies. That is risky and certainly opens the door to=C2=A0=
fraud, but it is a bit sad to get rid of it entirely.The other thing about =
projections is that they are really obviously important and useful. If you =
want to understand a company, particularly a young growing company, it is g=
enerally more useful to know how much money it will make next year than how=
 much money it made last year. And so=C2=A0companies that do IPOs make proj=
ections, and those projections find their way to investors. But gingerly, c=
arefully, and not in the official SEC filings. The company discusses its pr=
ojections with the research analysts at the underwriter banks, and the rese=
arch analysts discuss their own models with potential buyers of the IPO.[4]=
=C2=A0The IPO marketing process is a way for projections to filter out to b=
ig institutional buyers without putting those projections into SEC document=
s and having them be subject to litigation.It is kind of nice=C2=A0that in =
SPACs=C2=A0the projections go into the public filing for everyone to read, =
instead of being filtered through research analysts=E2=80=99 conversations =
with big institutional investors. In SPACs, everyone gets to read the same =
projections; in IPOs only the institutional investors get them. Presumably =
the institutional investors find them useful! Presumably they are useful! T=
hough sometimes they are wrong.=C2=A0The other thing that the SEC wants to =
do is increase disclosure of sponsor compensation and conflicts of interest=
. There is=C2=A0the usual disclosure-y stuff:=C2=A0We are proposing Item 16=
03(b) to require disclosure of any actual or potential material conflict of=
 interest between (1) the sponsor or its affiliates or the SPAC=E2=80=99s o=
fficers, directors, or promoters, and (2) unaffiliated security holders. Th=
is would include any conflict of interest in determining whether to proceed=
 with a de-SPAC transaction and any conflict of interest arising from the m=
anner in which a SPAC compensates the sponsor or the SPAC=E2=80=99s executi=
ve officers and directors, or the manner in which the sponsor compensates i=
ts own executive officers and=C2=A0directors.=C2=A0Doesn=E2=80=99t that jus=
t sound like it will generate boilerplate? =E2=80=9CWe may have a conflict =
of interest in which we will want to get a deal done more than you do,=E2=
=80=9D fine. Later there is a requirement for tabular disclosure of potenti=
al dilution:In light of the potential for significant dilution embedded wit=
hin the typical SPAC structure, enhanced disclosure regarding dilution coul=
d enable investors in a SPAC initial public offering and subsequent purchas=
ers of SPAC shares to better understand the potential impact upon them of t=
he various dilutive events that may occur over the lifespan of the SPAC. We=
 are therefore proposing to require dilution disclosure in registration sta=
tements filed by SPACs other than for de-SPAC transactions that would requi=
re a description of material potential sources of future dilution following=
 a SPAC=E2=80=99s initial public offering, as well as tabular disclosure of=
 the amount of potential future dilution from the public offering price tha=
t will be absorbed by nonredeeming SPAC shareholders, to the extent quantif=
iableSee, I would do a tabular disclosure of sponsor conflicts of interest.=
 Make the first page of a SPAC prospectus have=C2=A0a table like:=09This is=
 how much money the sponsor put in: _____=09This is how much money the spon=
sor will make if we do a deal and it goes up 100%: _____=09Up 20%: _____=09=
Flat: _____=09Down 20%: _____I feel like SPACs would go a bit differently i=
f they said, on the front page, =E2=80=9Cif we waste your money on a bad de=
al, and you approve it, we=E2=80=99ll get so rich.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0One more t=
hing in the proposed rules is that=C2=A0the prospectus for a de-SPAC merger=
 will have to have a section explaining whether the merger is fair to the S=
PAC shareholders. That requirement is sort of code for: =E2=80=9CYou will n=
eed to get a fairness opinion from an investment bank saying that the compa=
ny is worth what you=E2=80=99re paying for it.=E2=80=9D[5] I mean, a fairne=
ss opinion doesn=E2=80=99t exactly say that, but that is the rough implicat=
ion of it: The bankers, using some assumptions, come up with a range of val=
uations for the company, and the price you=E2=80=99re paying had better be =
in that range.This is actually a slightly=C2=A0higher=C2=A0bar than in an I=
PO. The bankers in an IPO will do some valuations =E2=80=94=C2=A0to pitch t=
heir services to the company, if nothing else =E2=80=94=C2=A0but at the end=
 of the day they will sell the IPO for whatever the market thinks it=E2=80=
=99s worth; they don=E2=80=99t have to sign an opinion saying that it=E2=80=
=99s worth that much. With SPACs, now, they will.
