   =20
      Who controls a company?
   =20
 =20
We have  talked a few  times about Arm China, a company that got mad at its=
 parent companies and moved out of their house. Arm Ltd. is a UK semiconduc=
tor company owned by SoftBank Group Corp. It has a joint venture in China (=
=E2=80=9CArm China=E2=80=9D); Arm Ltd. owns 47.3% of the joint venture. In =
2020, Arm Ltd. and another investor in the joint venture decided to fire th=
e chief executive officer of Arm China, Allen Wu. Wu declined to leave, kep=
t the corporate seals, fired Arm loyalists and kept his own people,=C2=A0hi=
red security guards to keep Arm out of the Arm China offices, announced tha=
t Arm China will be developing its own intellectual property, has mused abo=
ut taking Arm China public without Arm Ltd.=E2=80=99s approval,=C2=A0and re=
mains in control of Arm China to this day. There are lawsuits, oh are there=
 lawsuits. But there are also the brute facts of, like, the guards at the d=
oor listen to Wu.=C2=A0This creates=C2=A0odd legal and accounting=C2=A0prob=
lems for Arm Ltd. Arm China is a subsidiary of Arm Ltd.; the financial resu=
lts of Arm China affect the financial statements of Arm Ltd. Arm Ltd. would=
 like to go public. It needs audited financial statements to go public. It =
cannot get an audit because the security guards won=E2=80=99t let Arm Ltd.,=
 or presumably its auditors, in the door at Arm China. This is bad. If you =
operate your business through subsidiaries, and you want to go public, you =
have to tell the public about the operations of those subsidiaries. =E2=80=
=9CThe subsidiaries won=E2=80=99t talk to us so we=E2=80=99re not really su=
re what=E2=80=99s up with them=E2=80=9D is not good disclosure.=C2=A0Arm Ch=
ina is=C2=A0legally=C2=A0a subsidiary of Arm Ltd. subject to Arm Ltd.=E2=80=
=99s control, but it is=C2=A0factually=C2=A0an independent black box that s=
ometimes sends money back to Arm Ltd. in the form of licensing payments but=
, like, don=E2=80=99t count on it. Ideally Arm would resolve this conundrum=
 by taking factual control of Arm China again, but that seems tricky, becau=
se of the guards. The second-best approach is to resolve the conundrum by m=
aking Arm China legally a black box. The Financial Times reports:Arm is pla=
nning to transfer shares in its unwieldy China joint venture to a SoftBank =
special purpose vehicle in a bid to speed up the UK chip designer=E2=80=99s=
 path to a New York flotation.The British company has struggled to regain c=
ontrol of its China business for almost two years. Its inability to audit t=
he financials of the unit, which contributed about one-fifth of revenue las=
t year, is a big sticking point for a blockbuster public offering desired b=
y owner SoftBank following the collapse of Arm=E2=80=99s $66bn sale to Nvid=
ia last month.The share transfer, if successfully completed, will leave the=
 China joint venture tied to Arm headquarters through a licensing agreement=
, instead of the 47.3 per cent equity stake it holds today, according to tw=
o people briefed on the matter.Arm will continue receiving licensing revenu=
es from Arm China, but will not need to audit the company=E2=80=99s financi=
als, one of the people said.It=E2=80=99s the difference between saying =E2=
=80=9Cour auditors have visited Arm China and confirmed that it spent $25=
=C2=A0on salaries and $10 on rent while earning $50 in chip sales, our shar=
es of which are reflected in our consolidated financial statements=E2=80=9D=
 and =E2=80=9Clast quarter Arm China sent us a check for $15 and we cashed =
it and frankly were glad to get it.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
