   =20
      Block trades
   =20
 =20
Back in 2020 we talked about=C2=A0the trade-at-settlement mechanism in the =
oil futures market. The way TAS works is that sometime during the day, I ag=
ree to buy futures from you at the end of the day, at whatever the price is=
 at the end of the day plus or minus a few pennies. So we agree on a price =
of like =E2=80=9C+$0.02=E2=80=9D at noon, and then at the end of the tradin=
g session if the price of a futures contract is $40 per barrel I pay you $4=
0.02. We=E2=80=99re locked into a trade, and a size, and a discount or prem=
ium, but not a=C2=A0price; the price is set by whatever the closing price i=
s for the day.One issue with TAS trading is that, if you are selling me a b=
unch of futures at $0.02 above the closing price, you might decide to hedge=
 by buying those futures. You might buy them, not in the TAS market, but in=
 the regular futures market. You might choose to buy them right in the few =
minutes before the close. You might choose to do this as noisily as possibl=
e. You might thus drive up the price of futures right at the close. This wo=
uld make the settlement price very high. Because I have already agreed to b=
uy from you at the settlement price, whatever it is, this means that I woul=
d pay you more. You would make a lot of money.[6]The trick here is that you=
 and I have agreed on a trade based on a small discount or premium to the c=
losing price, which we don=E2=80=99t know yet. I am just a taker of the clo=
sing price: Whatever the closing price is, I pay you, plus $0.02. You, on t=
he other hand, understand that the move is to go out and influence the clos=
ing price: The higher it is, the more you make.There is a certain legal gra=
yness here: Sure, you can hedge your TAS exposure by buying futures in the =
regular market, but you can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0manipulate=C2=A0the settlement p=
rice by =E2=80=9Cbanging the close.=E2=80=9D Those things are very hard to =
distinguish from each other, unless you send your colleagues dumb electroni=
c chat messages saying like =E2=80=9Cbro i m banging the close, hope i dont=
 go to prizon.=E2=80=9DWe have talked a few times about an investigation in=
to Wall Street block trading.  The other day I described one way for a bloc=
k trade to work, which is that a company goes to some banks at around noon,=
 says =E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99ll have a block at the close, get ready to bi=
d,=E2=80=9D and then at 4 p.m. it asks them for bids, chooses the highest b=
idder, and sells that bank the stock. If the banks leak some information ab=
out the block to the market, the closing price will go down (because people=
 will know a lot of supply is coming), and they will be able to bid a lower=
 price.=C2=A0But this is not a perfect mechanism. Not just because it=E2=80=
=99s illegal, but also because the stock goes down for everyone. If I am on=
e of the banks who will bid at the close, and I drive the stock down and th=
en bid a bit below the closing price, everyone else can see that lower clos=
ing price and bid against me.But here is a Wall Street Journal story about =
suspicious stock drops in advance of block trades that points out that many=
 blocks work slightly differently=C2=A0from what I described:An investment =
bank agrees, generally around midday, to quietly buy the shares at a discou=
nt to the market=E2=80=99s closing price later that day. The bank then aims=
 to flip the stock to its trading clients at a higher price and pocket the =
difference. It is a clubby world: Four or five banks do the vast majority o=
f trades, and the same roster of hedge funds line up to buy the shares, acc=
ording to the data and market participants.That is, you don=E2=80=99t bid a=
t 4 p.m. against the closing price. You agree at noon to a=C2=A0fixed disco=
unt to the closing price. It=E2=80=99s a trade-at-settlement trade. The sel=
ler (a company or big shareholder) is a taker of the closing price, the buy=
er (the bank) =E2=80=A6=C2=A0might =E2=80=A6=C2=A0influence that price:The =
Journal=E2=80=99s analysis found that when Morgan Stanley executed a block =
trade by itself, the median stock trailed its peers by 0.7 percentage point=
 in the trading session leading up to the deal, meaning half performed wors=
e than that. That was the worst record of any of the biggest banks that are=
 major players in block trading. The median of Credit Suisse Group AG=E2=80=
=99s deals was underperformance of 0.4 percentage point, the analysis found=
. The median trades executed by Goldman and Barclays PLC roughly matched th=
e market.Across all banks, the median stock lagged by 0.2 percentage point.=
The more you plan to leak news about the block to your investor customers, =
the smaller the discount you need!=C2=A0
