getting blue and walking around seeing what happened as a social experiment=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy em=
ail form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you c=
an subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Tha=
nks![1] That is, the sponsor gets 20% of the SPAC shares for some nominal p=
rice. If the SPAC sells 10 million shares at $10 each, it raises $100 milli=
on; the sponsor will get 2.5 million shares, 20% of the SPAC=E2=80=99s 12.5=
 million share total. If the deal is completed, the sponsor=E2=80=99s share=
s become shares of the combined company, just like the public shares. If a =
deal is not completed, the public shareholders get their $10 back and the s=
ponsor=E2=80=99s shares are worthless. Also I am saying =E2=80=9Cthe money =
raised=E2=80=9D but I mean the money raised in the initial SPAC offering, w=
hich is not necessarily the money raised *for the company*, because SPAC in=
vestors can ask for their money back. If half of them do, and the deal stil=
l closes, then the sponsor=E2=80=99s take is effectively 50% of the money r=
aised.[2] One other, more technical point is that the SEC will clarify that=
 most normal SPACS =E2=80=94=C2=A0ones that put their money into government=
 securities while looking for a deal, sign one within 18 months and close i=
t within two years =E2=80=94=C2=A0are not =E2=80=9Cinvestment companies,=E2=
=80=9D that is, mutual funds. Being an investment company would subject SPA=
Cs to a bunch of other rules, particularly about conflicts of interest, and=
 would make it much harder for sponsors to get their economics from a SPAC.=
=C2=A0Nobody really thought that SPACs *were* investment companies, but las=
t year two law professors  brought a clever lawsuit against Bill Ackman arg=
uing that his SPAC was, and also that all SPACs might be investment compani=
es. The SEC is now clarifying that, no, most SPACs are not investment compa=
nies, though I=E2=80=99m not sure that the SEC=E2=80=99s safe harbor would =
apply to Ackman=E2=80=99s SPAC.=C2=A0[3] Technically it would treat them li=
ke =E2=80=9Cblank check companies,=E2=80=9D which under current SEC rules m=
eans basically a penny-stock SPAC. That was always kind of a weird definiti=
on; everyone calls SPACs blank-check companies anyway, but under existing S=
EC rules they aren=E2=80=99t.[4] Latham & Watkins LLP has a good =E2=80=9CU=
S IPO Guide=E2=80=9D describing the whole process. A key section: =E2=80=9C=
The research analyst at each of your lead investment banks will create his =
or her own financial model based in part on what he or she learns on analys=
t day and in subsequent one-on-one diligence sessions with you. The analyst=
s will have myriad questions about the company, its business, its strategy,=
 and the management model, and each analyst will produce his or her own pro=
prietary model, which can be expected to differ in some ways from the manag=
ement model. You will not share projections with potential IPO investors du=
ring the road show (except in some MLP and REIT deals), but the analysts ma=
y verbally discuss their proprietary models with potential IPO investors on=
ce the offering has launched. The analysts=E2=80=99 models may include grow=
th rates and margin assumptions specific to your business as well as other =
metrics based on your industry. It is important to ensure that the analysts=
 are not basing their projections of future growth or profitability on outd=
ated, inaccurate, or incomplete information, as the information that you pr=
ovide will be the basis for many of the assumptions that they make and shar=
e with buy-side clients during this investor education process.=E2=80=9D Al=
so: =E2=80=9CThe research analysts at your syndicate banks will want freque=
nt chances to meet and speak with you to discuss your company, its business=
es, and its strategy, and to review management=E2=80=99s projections for th=
e next several years (typically quarter-by-quarter for the next two years a=
nd then year-by-year for another year or so thereafter). A group meeting wi=
th the syndicate analysts typically will occur around the third month of th=
e process, usually referred to as =E2=80=9Canalyst day.=E2=80=9D Unlike the=
 investment bankers who have been helping you prepare your registration sta=
tement, the research analysts do not work for you. They are independent and=
 the research they prepare must reflect their personal views, without influ=
ence or pressure from investment banking, issuer management, or other exter=
nal forces. Your meetings with research analysts are very important because=
 these analysts are going to help educate the market about your company onc=
e the transaction has launched.=E2=80=9D[5] From the dissenting statement o=
f SEC Commissioner Hester Peirce: =E2=80=9CWhile this disclosure requiremen=
t technically does not require a SPAC board to hire third parties to conduc=
t analyses and prepare a fairness opinion, the proposed rules clearly conte=
mplate that this is the likely outcome of the new requirement. For example,=
 the proposal would require disclosure of whether =E2=80=98an unaffiliated =
representative=E2=80=99=C2=A0has been retained to either negotiate the de-S=
PAC transaction or prepare a fairness opinion and would elicit disclosures =
about =E2=80=98any report, opinion, or appraisal from an outside party rela=
ting to . . . the fairness of the de-SPAC transaction.=E2=80=99 For state l=
aw reasons, fairness opinions are common in many merger transactions, but (=
as the economic analysis acknowledges) they are not standard in de-SPAC tra=
nsactions.=E2=80=9D[6] To be clear, you=E2=80=99d make a lot of money becau=
se all your sales (to me) would occur at the settlement price, a single poi=
nt in time, while your purchases (from the market) would occur at a range o=
f prices over some time period. If you do this right, that time period is l=
ike the 10 minutes before the close, and each purchase pushes up the price.=
 So you start buying at $35 and finish at $40, buying at an average price o=
f $37.50, and then turn around and sell all of it to=C2=A0me at $40.02.
