<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow and Monday, back on Tuesday.</em></p><table class=
=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0"=
>
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SPAC rules</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People have two main objections to spe=
cial purpose acquisition companies, the blank-check companies that raise a =
pool of money from public investors and then use it to take some private co=
mpany public. First: Sometimes it can look like the=C2=A0<em>private compan=
y=C2=A0</em>is running a scam. Going public by merging with a SPAC is an al=
ternative to a traditional initial public offering with somewhat more relax=
ed rules. In particular, it is generally accepted that SPAC targets can inc=
lude=C2=A0<em>projected future earnings=C2=A0</em>in their filings marketin=
g their deal, while IPO companies can=E2=80=99t. If you are a high-tech com=
pany with big dreams but no revenue yet, it is nice to be able to say =E2=
=80=9Cwell look how good our 2025 revenue is.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Then if your 20=
25 revenue also turns out to be zero, well, you know, that=E2=80=99s fine, =
mistakes happen. There is a =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/27214433.269607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3Vz=
Y29kZS90ZXh0LzE1Lzc4dS01/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBba52d112" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">safe ha=
rbor for forward-looking statements</a>=E2=80=9D; if your predictions were =
in good faith but turn out to be wrong, you can=E2=80=99t get sued. IPO com=
panies don=E2=80=99t get this safe harbor, but SPAC companies do.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second: Sometimes it can look like the <em>SPAC spon=
sor</em> is running a scam. The sponsor is the person who raises the pool o=
f money and goes out and finds a private company to merge with. Generally s=
he will put up a little bit of her own money to pay for lawyers etc., and i=
f she completes a deal her reward will be shares in the public company equa=
l to 25% of the money raised.[1] This rubs people the wrong way, first of a=
ll, because 25% is just a really big commission.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">But also it creates bad incentives. SPACs have a limited life; =
generally they have to do a merger within two years. If the SPAC does a mer=
ger, the sponsor gets 25% of the money raised. If the SPAC does not do a me=
rger in time, it has to give investors back their money, and the sponsor ge=
ts nothing. The sponsor is going to really, really, really want to do a dea=
l. If she does a deal that is=C2=A0<em>bad</em>, that is fine, for her. If =
the sponsor of a $100 million SPAC gets a deal done, and the stock drops 20=
% after it closes,=C2=A0then she gets $20 million; if she doesn=E2=80=99t g=
et the deal done she gets zero. It=E2=80=99s the opposite for the sharehold=
ers of the SPAC: If the deal doesn=E2=80=99t happen, they get their $100 mi=
llion back; if it does, and drops 20%, then they only get $80 million and h=
ave a $20 million loss. The shareholders have to approve the deal, but this=
 gives the sponsor powerful incentives to be optimistic about the deal.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission do=
es not particularly like SPACs, and yesterday it <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27214433.269607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9u=
ZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi01Ng/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB54cf30d9" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">proposed new rules</a> to make clear its displeasure. There are a bunch =
of rules but broadly speaking they are aimed at the two main problems I ide=
ntified above.[2]=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First, the SEC want=
s to get rid of projections in SPACs, and generally tighten up the rules ar=
ound liability for how SPACs market themselves. There is a sense now that i=
f you do an IPO, everything you say in the IPO prospectus has to be true, w=
hile if you go public via SPAC you get a bit more creative license. The SEC=
 wants to do away with that and put SPACs and IPOs on equal footing.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It does this in several ways. The main one is tha=
t it gets rid of the safe harbor for SPACs=E2=80=99 forward-looking stateme=
nts. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27214433.=
269607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE1Lzc4dS01/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCba52d112" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">safe harbor says that</a> big exist=
ing public companies can make statements about the future, and as long as (=
1) they publish boilerplate warnings saying =E2=80=9Cthese statements might=
 not come true=E2=80=9D and (2) they don=E2=80=99t have =E2=80=9Cactual kno=
wledge ... that the statement was false or misleading,=E2=80=9D then they c=
an=E2=80=99t be sued for them. But this is not true of companies doing an i=
nitial public offering; basically if they say stuff that is wrong they can =
be sued. So in practice IPO documents do not contain projections. Right now=
 people seem to think (though it is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/27214433.269607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMTIvbWF5YmUtc3BhY3MtYXJlLXJlYWxseS1pcG9zP2NtcGlk=
PUJCRDAzMzEyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV=
0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDMzMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB649d4cb1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> not free from doubt</a>) that SPACs are trea=
ted like regular public companies, but the SEC=E2=80=99s new rule would tre=
at them like IPO companies.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there ar=
e also other rule changes that have the effect of warning everyone in the v=
icinity of a SPAC that if the disclosure is wrong, they will get sued. The =
SEC will treat the de-SPAC merger =E2=80=94=C2=A0the transaction in which t=
he SPAC merges with the private company, taking it public =E2=80=94=C2=A0as=
 a public offering of securities. It will treat the private company as a =
=E2=80=9Cco-registrant=E2=80=9D of the SPAC, making it liable for everythin=
g in the prospectus. An investment bank that underwrites the initial SPAC o=
ffering and also works on the de-SPAC merger will be treated as an underwri=
ter of that de-SPAC merger, potentially=C2=A0making=C2=A0<em>it </em>liable=
 for=C2=A0errors in the merger prospectus. (Presumably this will increase t=
he fees that the banks charge SPACs.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On on=
e level it is hard to object to this. It is weird to have two ways of going=
 public, one of which (a SPAC) allows you to exaggerate and one of which (a=
n IPO) does not. And when you put it like that it does seem like the not-ex=
aggerating=C2=A0approach is preferable to the exaggerating=C2=A0one. Also t=
here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27214433.2=
69607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktM=
jkvaW5zaWRlcnMtYXJlLWdvb2QtYXQtdHJhZGluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzMxMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVG=
RiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAzMzE=
mdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2258a940" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> some evidence</a> that (1) investors pay=C2=A0attention to optimistic pro=
jections in de-SPAC mergers and (2) those projections are <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27214433.269607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMjgvcnVzc2lhLXMtbW9uZXktaX=
MtZ29uZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzMxMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb=
3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAzMzEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3a0357ee" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> not very good</a>, which you mi=
ght expect from, you know, being allowed to exaggerate.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand. The intuitive sorting between SPACs=
 and IPOs, under the current rules, is not exactly =E2=80=9Creal companies =
do IPOs and fake companies do SPACs.=E2=80=9D It is more like =E2=80=9Ccomp=
anies with a few years of impressive revenue growth do IPOs, while companie=
s whose main product is still a prototype do SPACs.=E2=80=9D (This is not a=
lways true either way, by any means, but it is a rough heuristic.) If you a=
re working on building a flying electric taxi or whatever, (1) that=E2=80=
=99s kind of cool, (2) it will cost a lot of money, (3) if it works you=E2=
=80=99ll probably make a lot of money and (4) it might not work. If you go =
to public-market investors and say =E2=80=9Chi, I want to build flying elec=
tric taxis, my revenue last year was zero and I spend $50 million on salari=
es and components,=E2=80=9D that is not a compelling pitch. If you go to th=
em and say =E2=80=9Chi, I want to build flying electric taxis, if all goes =
well we=E2=80=99ll bring in a billion dollars of revenue in 2024,=E2=80=9D =
they will be like =E2=80=9Coh cool flying taxis!=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">This is bad for them if you fail to build flying electric ta=
xis and good for them if you succeed wildly. And of course you might be run=
ning a scam. But against a general backdrop in which companies that go publ=
ic are increasingly old, large and established, there is something nice abo=
ut SPACs being a way for companies to go public earlier. SPACs can be a way=
 for public markets to provide venture-type capital to young ambitious comp=
anies, particularly green-tech companies. That is risky and certainly opens=
 the door to=C2=A0fraud, but it is a bit sad to get rid of it entirely.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other thing about projections is that they=
 are really obviously important and useful. If you want to understand a com=
pany, particularly a young growing company, it is generally more useful to =
know how much money it will make next year than how much money it made last=
 year. And so=C2=A0<em>companies that do IPOs make projections, and those p=
rojections find their way to investors</em>. But gingerly, carefully, and n=
ot in the official SEC filings. The company discusses its projections with =
the research analysts at the underwriter banks, and the research analysts d=
iscuss their own models with potential buyers of the IPO.[4]=C2=A0The IPO m=
arketing process is a way for projections to filter out to big institutiona=
l buyers without putting those projections into SEC documents and having th=
em be subject to litigation.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is kind of =
<em>nice=C2=A0</em>that in SPACs=C2=A0the projections go into the public fi=
ling for everyone to read, instead of being filtered through research analy=
sts=E2=80=99 conversations with big institutional investors. In SPACs, ever=
yone gets to read the same projections; in IPOs only the institutional inve=
stors get them. Presumably the institutional investors find them useful! Pr=
esumably they are useful! Though sometimes they are wrong.=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other thing that the SEC wants to do is increase =
disclosure of sponsor compensation and conflicts of interest. There is=C2=
=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27214433.269607=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9ydWxlcy9wcm9wb3NlZC8yMDIyLzMzLTExMDQ4LnBkZg/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB76ee2951" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the usual disclosure-y stuff</a>:=
=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We are proposing Item 16=
03(b) to require disclosure of any actual or potential material conflict of=
 interest between (1) the sponsor or its affiliates or the SPAC=E2=80=99s o=
fficers, directors, or promoters, and (2) unaffiliated security holders. Th=
is would include any conflict of interest in determining whether to proceed=
 with a de-SPAC transaction and any conflict of interest arising from the m=
anner in which a SPAC compensates the sponsor or the SPAC=E2=80=99s executi=
ve officers and directors, or the manner in which the sponsor compensates i=
ts own executive officers and=C2=A0directors.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Doesn=E2=80=99t that just sound like it will generate=
 boilerplate? =E2=80=9CWe may have a conflict of interest in which we will =
want to get a deal done more than you do,=E2=80=9D fine. Later there is a r=
equirement for tabular disclosure of potential dilution:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In light of the potential for significant dilutio=
n embedded within the typical SPAC structure, enhanced disclosure regarding=
 dilution could enable investors in a SPAC initial public offering and subs=
equent purchasers of SPAC shares to better understand the potential impact =
upon them of the various dilutive events that may occur over the lifespan o=
f the SPAC. We are therefore proposing to require dilution disclosure in re=
gistration statements filed by SPACs other than for de-SPAC transactions th=
at would require a description of material potential sources of future dilu=
tion following a SPAC=E2=80=99s initial public offering, as well as tabular=
 disclosure of the amount of potential future dilution from the public offe=
ring price that will be absorbed by nonredeeming SPAC shareholders, to the =
extent quantifiable</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See, I wou=
ld do a tabular disclosure of sponsor conflicts of interest. Make the first=
 page of a SPAC prospectus have=C2=A0a table like:</p><ul style=3D"list-sty=
le-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">This is how much money the sponsor put in: _____</li>=09<li s=
