et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> The other day</a> I described one way for =
a block trade to work, which is that a company goes to some banks at around=
 noon, says =E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99ll have a block at the close, get ready=
 to bid,=E2=80=9D and then at 4 p.m. it asks them for bids, chooses the hig=
hest bidder, and sells that bank the stock. If the banks leak some informat=
ion about the block to the market, the closing price will go down (because =
people will know a lot of supply is coming), and they will be able to bid a=
 lower price.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this is not a perfe=
ct mechanism. Not just because it=E2=80=99s illegal, but also because the s=
tock goes down for everyone. If I am one of the banks who will bid at the c=
lose, and I drive the stock down and then bid a bit below the closing price=
, everyone else can see that lower closing price and bid against me.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But here is a Wall Street Journal story about sus=
picious stock drops in advance of block trades that points out that <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27214433.269607/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9iaWctc3RvY2stc2FsZXMtYXJlLXN1cHBvc2VkLXRvLWJl=
LXNlY3JldC10aGUtbnVtYmVycy1pbmRpY2F0ZS10aGV5LWFyZW50LTExNjQ4NjQ3OTE0P21vZD1=
ocF9sZWFkX3BvczM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4566f171" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">many blocks wor=
k slightly differently</a>=C2=A0from what I described:</p><blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An investment bank agrees, generally around midday,=
 to quietly buy the shares at a discount to the market=E2=80=99s closing pr=
ice later that day. The bank then aims to flip the stock to its trading cli=
ents at a higher price and pocket the difference. It is a clubby world: Fou=
r or five banks do the vast majority of trades, and the same roster of hedg=
e funds line up to buy the shares, according to the data and market partici=
pants.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, you don=E2=80=
=99t bid at 4 p.m. against the closing price. You agree at noon to a=C2=A0<=
em>fixed discount to the closing price</em>. It=E2=80=99s a trade-at-settle=
ment trade. The seller (a company or big shareholder) is a taker of the clo=
sing price, the buyer (the bank) =E2=80=A6=C2=A0might =E2=80=A6=C2=A0influe=
nce that price:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Journal=E2=
=80=99s analysis found that when Morgan Stanley executed a block trade by i=
tself, the median stock trailed its peers by 0.7 percentage point in the tr=
ading session leading up to the deal, meaning half performed worse than tha=
t. That was the worst record of any of the biggest banks that are major pla=
yers in block trading. The median of Credit Suisse Group AG=E2=80=99s deals=
 was underperformance of 0.4 percentage point, the analysis found. The medi=
an trades executed by Goldman and Barclays PLC roughly matched the market.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Across all banks, the median stock lagged b=
y 0.2 percentage point.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The mo=
re you plan to leak news about the block to your investor customers, the sm=
aller the discount you need!=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%=
